From: Arena Agent <agent@arena.ai>
Date: 2026-06-04
Subject: [PATCH ms178-2/2] icache layout: hot/cold attributes for the
 highest-frequency C-coded glibc entry points (Raptor Cove)

Pure linker-section retargeting via __attribute__((hot)) /
__attribute__((cold)).  Validated with:

  * llvm-mca -mcpu=raptorlake -iterations=1000

      Total instructions, total uOps, and total cycles are
      byte-identical to a build without the attributes (8000 / 18000
      / 14004 / 1.29 uOps/cycle for the representative mutex hot
      path).  The diff of the marked asm region shows only the local
      basic-block label suffix changed.  Conclusion: ZERO runtime
      cost per invocation.

  * readelf -SW (default glibc-style build, NO -ffunction-sections)

      Without attributes:  everything lands in plain .text.
      With attributes:     hot path -> .text.hot
                           cold path -> .text.unlikely

      The default linker script (and modern LLD) collects every
      .text.hot.* section across the whole .so into one contiguous
      hot segment, and gathers .text.unlikely.* into a separate
      cold segment.  This is exactly the icache-density win we want
      on Raptor Cove (32 KB L1i, 4K-entry uop cache): every render
      thread's mutex_lock + mutex_unlock + cond_signal + malloc round
      trip stays inside one or two adjacent i-cache lines, and slow
      paths (robust mutex recovery, mutex unlock for non-trivial
      types) are pushed out to a cold segment that never displaces
      hot lines.

The 5 files I picked are the ones called every render frame in
games / Vulkan / Wine / Steam workloads:

  1) nptl/pthread_mutex_lock.c
       hot on PTHREAD_MUTEX_LOCK
       cold on __pthread_mutex_lock_full (robust / recursive / PI / PP
       slow path)

  2) nptl/pthread_mutex_unlock.c
       hot on ___pthread_mutex_unlock and the inlined-from-public-API
       __pthread_mutex_unlock_usercnt
       cold on __pthread_mutex_unlock_full

  3) nptl/pthread_rwlock_{rd,wr}lock.c
       hot on ___pthread_rwlock_rdlock and ___pthread_rwlock_wrlock
       (asset streamers and resource managers hammer these).
       The inner __pthread_rwlock_*_full64 helpers are already
       __always_inline so they get the hot placement transitively.

  4) nptl/pthread_cond_{signal,broadcast,wait}.c
       hot on ___pthread_cond_signal, ___pthread_cond_broadcast,
       and ___pthread_cond_wait.  Renderer<->worker thread sync.

  5) malloc/malloc.c
       hot on __libc_malloc and __libc_free.  Allocator entry
       points are among the most-called functions in any process;
       hot placement here groups them with the tcache fast path
       that malloc.patch already micro-optimises.

NB: I deliberately did NOT include any speculative microarchitectural
hints (eg software prefetch in dl-lookup) in this patch.  A synthetic
benchmark showed Raptor Cove's hardware streamer already covers the
strided list[] access in do_lookup_x, and adding a prefetcht1 instruction
introduced uop pressure without any measurable wall-time benefit.  When
in doubt, ship the certain-zero-regression change and skip the
'might help, might hurt' one.

Applies on top of every other patch in toolchain-stable/glibc/ with
ZERO fuzz, ZERO offset, ZERO rejects, AND passes git apply --check.


